INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442001, 'Blue, green, grey, white, or black; smooth, ruffled, or mountainous; that ocean is not silent.', 1060, 0), (442002, 'Simplicity is natures first step, and the last of art.', 1151, 0), (442003, 'There is an electric fire in human nature tending to purify - so that among these human creatures there is continually some birth of new heroism. The pity is that we must wonder at it, as we should at finding a pearl in rubbish.', 191, 0), (442004, 'There is no glory in star or blossom till looked upon by a loving eye There is no fragrance in April breezes till breathed with joy as they wander by. ', 70801, 0), (442005, 'It is a holy blessing to be born with the exquisite qualities of a daughter of God. Women of God, both old and young, are spiritual and sensitive, tender and gentle. They have a kind, nurturing nature. This is your inheritance. Never belittle the gifts God has given to you. Develop the divinity that is within you.', 70311, 0), (442006, 'This sunlight linked me through the ages to that past consciousness.', 69945, 0), (442007, 'To me a lush carpet of pine needles or spongy grass is more welcome than the most luxurious Persian rug.', 701, 0), (442008, 'Birds have wings they''re free they can fly where they want when they want. They have the kind of mobility many people envy. ', 70825, 0), (442009, 'While we are under the tyranny of Priests, it will ever be their interest, to invalidate the law of nature and reason, in order to establish systems incompatible therewith.', 25914, 0), (442010, 'All nature is but art unknown to thee.', 3348, 0), (442011, 'The good is, like nature, an immense landscape in which man advances through centuries of exploration.', 2800, 0), (442012, 'When women reassert their relationship with the wildish nature, they are gifted with a permanent and internal watcher, a knower, a visionary, an oracle, an inspiratrice, an intuitive, a maker, a creator, an inventor, and a listener who guide, suggest, and urge vibrant life in the inner and outer world.', 625, 0), (442013, 'Purity and simplicity are the two wings with which man soars above the earth and all temporary nature.', 946, 0), (442014, 'Perhaps nature is our best assurance of immortality.', 141, 0), (442015, 'Nature chooses who will be transgender individuals don''t choose this. ', 70826, 0), (442016, 'Nature has given women so much power that the law has very wisely given them little.', 2087, 0), (442017, 'Now that I''m older, I have a much better appreciation of nature, and I love being alone.', 69323, 0), (442018, 'What I''m attempting to do is to show people that if I can spend some time with very dangerous spiders and snakes and scorpions, then maybe they''ll feel different about the spiders and snakes they find around their areas. I don''t need people to keep them as pets. I just like them to be respectful and see that everything in nature has its place.', 45050, 0), (442019, 'When there is in nature no fixed condition, how much less must there be in the life of a people, beings endowed with mobility and movement!', 3961, 0), (442020, 'We are all full of weakness and errors let us mutually pardon each other our follies - it is the first law of nature. ', 808, 0), (442021, 'Nature abhors a hero. For one thing, he violates the law of conservation of energy. For another, how can it be the survival of the fittest when the fittest keeps putting himself in situations where he is most likely to be creamed?', 70827, 0), (442022, 'The increase of scientific knowledge lies not only in the occasional milestones of science, but in the efforts of the very large body of men who with love and devotion observe and study nature.', 70828, 0), (442023, 'I had to live in the desert before I could understand the full value of grass in a green ditch.', 70829, 0), (442024, 'The thing that gave me the most pain in life, psychologically, and it gave me tremendous pain psychologically, is man''s disrespect for nature.', 16696, 0), (442025, 'If we could establish a deep abiding relationship with nature, we would never kill an animal for our appetite; we would never harm, vivisect, a monkey, a dog, a guinea pig for our benefit. We would find other ways to heal our wounds, heal our bodies.', 1780, 0), (442026, 'This magnificent butterfly finds a little heap of dirt and sits still on it but man will never on his heap of mud keep still. ', 1241, 0), (442027, 'In the Spring, I have counted 136 different kinds of weather inside of 24 hours.', 286, 0), (442028, 'Nature has never read the Declaration of Independence. It continues to make us unequal.', 1167, 0), (442029, 'Nature uses human imagination to lift her work of creation to even higher levels.', 23247, 0), (442030, 'The beautiful spring came; and when Nature resumes her loveliness, the human soul is apt to revive also.', 70830, 0), (442031, 'Human nature is not nearly as bad as it has been thought to be.', 62519, 0), (442032, 'Envy is human nature.', 47394, 0), (442033, 'Borrow trouble for yourself, if that''s your nature, but don''t lend it to your neighbours.', 843, 0), (442034, 'Man is the unnatural animal, the rebel child of nature, and more and more does he turn himself against the harsh and fitful hand that reared him.', 3173, 0), (442035, 'To become an able and successful man in any profession, three things are necessary, nature, study and practice.', 2175, 0), (442036, 'I think that in today''s world, by nature, we are all self-centered. And that often leads to selfishness.', 956, 0), (442037, 'We should attempt to bring nature, houses, and human beings together in a higher unity.', 67443, 0), (442038, 'I quickly realized that shopping on Amazon had made the idea of parking my car and going into a store feel like an outrageous imposition on my time and good nature.', 6299, 0), (442039, 'The way of the Creative works through change and transformation, so that each thing receives its true nature and destiny and comes into permanent accord with the Great Harmony: this is what furthers and what perseveres.', 3348, 0), (442040, 'The landscape painter must walk in the fields with a humble mind. No arrogant man was ever permitted to see Nature in all her beauty.', 70831, 0), (442041, 'Teaching man his relatively small sphere in the creation, it also encourages him by its lessons of the unity of Nature and shows him that his power of comprehension allies him with the great intelligence over-reaching all.', 70832, 0), (442042, 'If one way be better than another, that you may be sure is nature''s way.', 1116, 0), (442043, 'What would be ugly in a garden constitutes beauty in a mountain.', 98, 0), (442044, 'Our body is a machine for living. It is organized for that, it is its nature. Let life go on in it unhindered and let it defend itself.', 93, 0), (442045, 'I think it is in collaboration that the nature of art is revealed.', 70833, 0), (442046, 'I have a bit of a rebellious nature.', 70232, 0), (442047, 'He who looks the higher is the more highly distinguished, and turning over the great book of nature (which is the proper object of philosophy) is the way to elevate one''s gaze.', 1705, 0), (442048, 'Bald as the bare mountain tops are bald, with a baldness full of grandeur.', 460, 0), (442049, 'Physics is about questioning, studying, probing nature. You probe, and, if you''re lucky, you get strange clues.', 70183, 0), (442050, 'I think... the history of civilization is an attempt to codify, classify and categorize aspects of human nature that hardly lend themselves to that process.', 408, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442051, 'And muse on Nature with a poet''s eye.', 7779, 0), (442052, 'I''ll walk where my own nature would be leading: It vexes me to choose another guide.', 55, 0), (442053, 'I''m a diplomat by nature. I help find the middle ground. I crack a joke and use humour to help resolve potentially vicious situations quickly. It gets things in perspective and helps everyone to see that things aren''t as bad as they seem.', 70834, 0), (442054, 'Ocean: A body of water occupying about two-thirds of a world made for man - who has no gills.', 224, 0), (442055, 'There is the sky, which is all men''s together.', 542, 0), (442056, 'It is written on the arched sky it looks out from every star. It is the poetry of Nature it is that which uplifts the spirit within us. ', 485, 0), (442057, 'Although I do wrong, I do not the wrongs that I am charged with doing; the wrong that I do is through the frailty of human nature, like other men. No man lives without fault.', 3554, 0), (442058, 'Military deployments have never been something to enjoy, but the consequence of the actions, the shared nature of the sacrifices, and the nobility of the cause are invigorating. To be clear, I''m not talking about the killing and the death; rather, the sense of purpose that pervades every action, reaction, and outcome.', 70835, 0), (442059, 'Time is nature''s way of keeping everything from happening at once.', 10844, 0), (442060, 'Nature is the mother and the habitat of man, even if sometimes a stepmother and an unfriendly home.', 2575, 0), (442061, 'There''s a constantly applicable nature to soul music, whereas sometimes pop music can be a periodical.', 861, 0), (442062, 'Nature is infinitely creative. It is always producing the possibility of new beginnings.', 534, 0), (442063, 'I like to be grounded by nature, go hiking... go to an isolated island that''s not glamorous and touristy at all.', 70836, 0), (442064, 'I would warn you that I do not attribute to nature either beauty or deformity, order or confusion. Only in relation to our imagination can things be called beautiful or ugly, well-ordered or confused.', 2478, 0), (442065, 'There are grounds for cautious optimism that we may now be near the end ofthe search for the ultimate laws of nature.', 1222, 0), (442066, 'That the sea is one of the most beautiful and magnificent sights in Nature, all admit.', 70837, 0), (442067, 'If the machine of government is of such a nature that it requires you to be the agent of injustice to another, then, I say, break the law.', 1049, 0), (442068, 'The sway of alcohol over mankind is unquestionably due to its power to stimulate the mystical faculties of human nature, usually crushed to earth by the cold facts and dry criticisms of the sober hour.', 1782, 0), (442069, 'I slow down when hiking. The rhythm of nature is more leisurely. The sun comes up, it moves across the sky, and you begin to synchronize to that rhythm.', 66656, 0), (442070, 'Whatever the universal nature assigns to any man at any time is for the good of that man at that time.', 267, 0), (442071, 'Don''t knock the weather nine-tenths of the people couldn''t start a conversation if it didn''t change once in a while. ', 14120, 0), (442072, 'The groves were God''s first temples.', 70801, 0), (442073, 'The little windflower, whose just opened eye is blue as the spring heaven it gazes at.', 70801, 0), (442074, 'The principle that human nature, in its psychological aspects, is nothing more than a product of history and given social relations removes all barriers to coercion and manipulation by the powerful.', 1955, 0), (442075, 'We are learning, too, that the love of beauty is one of Nature''s greatest healers.', 54126, 0), (442076, 'Regardless of the nature of their crime or any rehabilitation that may have occurred, these ex-felons cannot participate in the decision-making process of this great Nation.', 41313, 0), (442077, 'From the dawn of history, science has probed the universe of unknowns, searching for the uniting laws of nature.', 67551, 0), (442078, 'The physical ego serves as its own worst enemy when, by delusive material behavior, it eclipses its true nature as the ever blessed soul.', 2055, 0), (442079, 'Art will never be able to exist without nature.', 70198, 0), (442080, 'Now where there are no parts, there neither extension, nor shape, nor divisibility is possible. And these monads are the true atoms of nature and, in a word, the elements of things.', 70838, 0), (442081, 'To conquer nature is, in effect, to remove all natural barriers and human norms and to substitute artificial, fabricated equivalents for natural processes.', 66828, 0), (442082, 'It is not human nature we should accuse but the despicable conventions that pervert it.', 2879, 0), (442083, 'Human nature is above all things lazy.', 3252, 0), (442084, 'Scientists and philosophers tend to treat knowledge, imagination and love as if they were all very separate parts of human nature. But when it comes to children, all three are deeply entwined. Children learn the truth by imagining all the ways the world could be, and testing those possibilities.', 20620, 0), (442085, 'Ever since I was a small child, I''ve had this feeling - it''s in my nature, and so it''s not even pretentious - that if everyone''s going one way, I will go the other, just by some kind of spirit of defiance.', 70839, 0), (442086, 'I think African Americans are resilient and hustlers by nature. I think they need to understand that you can take that hustle to the boardroom, but it has to be an education process.', 34921, 0), (442087, 'I have pets, but they''re the really ordinary sort - yellow Labrador, tabby cat, white rabbit, a few goldfish - that kind of stuff. Nothing very... extravagant or unusual or exotic, but I find, in terms of inspiration, Mother Nature is just it.', 70840, 0), (442088, 'By nature, I am a low-key person and like being behind the camera.', 70841, 0), (442089, 'The utilization of flat roofs as ''grounds'' offers us a means of re-acclimatizing nature amidst the stony deserts of our great towns for the plots from which she has been evicted to make room for buildings can be given back to her up aloft. ', 10311, 0), (442090, 'How are the faculties of man to be best developed and his happiness secured? The state of a king is not favorable to this, nor the state of the noble and rich men of the earth. All this is artificial life, the inventions of vanity and grasping ambition, by which we have spoiled the man of nature and of pure, simple, and undistorted impulses.', 20151, 0), (442091, 'We are a family that lives probably 90 percent on wild game. We''re certainly working our way toward 100 percent self-sufficient. Looking to raise chickens for eggs, things of that nature, start a garden. We enjoy the simple life.', 36579, 0), (442092, 'Whatever you are by nature, keep to it; never desert your line of talent. Be what nature intended you for, and you will succeed.', 9771, 0), (442093, 'The Republican form of government is the highest form of government: but because of this it requires the highest type of human nature, a type nowhere at present existing.', 3690, 0), (442094, 'Nature is the most beautiful thing we have. It''s better than art because it''s from the creator.', 69114, 0), (442095, 'The artist produces for the liberation of his soul. It is his nature to create as it is the nature of water to run down the hill.', 235, 0), (442096, 'Revenge is a kind of wild justice, which the more a man''s nature runs to, the more ought law to weed it out.', 1035, 0), (442097, 'None of us is responsible for the complexion of his skin. This fact of nature offers no clue to the character or quality of the person underneath.', 15432, 0), (442098, 'Let who will boast their courage in the field, I find but little safety from my shield, Nature''s, not honour''s law we must obey: This made me cast my useless shield away.', 62154, 0), (442099, 'Be truthful, nature only sides with truth.', 30052, 0), (442100, 'I remember a hundred lovely lakes, and recall the fragrant breath of pine and fir and cedar and poplar trees. The trail has strung upon it, as upon a thread of silk, opalescent dawns and saffron sunsets.', 21437, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442101, 'What we observe is not nature itself, but nature exposed to our method of questioning.', 2422, 0), (442102, 'Only that thing is free which exists by the necessities of its own nature, and is determined in its actions by itself alone.', 2478, 0), (442103, 'Spring is when you feel like whistling even with a shoe full of slush.', 5026, 0), (442104, 'Spring won''t let me stay in this house any longer! I must get out and breathe the air deeply again.', 49246, 0), (442105, 'In some mysterious way woods have never seemed to me to be static things. In physical terms, I move through them; yet in metaphysical ones, they seem to move through me.', 1452, 0), (442106, 'One could not pluck a flower without troubling a star.', 1812, 0), (442107, 'Nature abhors annihilation.', 1306, 0), (442108, 'The sun, the moon and the stars would have disappeared long ago... had they happened to be within the reach of predatory human hands.', 62533, 0), (442109, 'The Universe is one great kindergarten for man. Everything that exists has brought with it its own peculiar lesson.', 4025, 0), (442110, 'I consider myself to have been the bridge between the shotgun and the binoculars in bird watching. Before I came along, the primary way to observe birds was to shoot them and stuff them.', 70825, 0), (442111, 'Oh, the summer night, Has a smile of light, And she sits on a sapphire throne.', 69102, 0), (442112, 'Having contemplated this admirable grove, I proceeded towards the shrubberies on the banks of the river, and though it was now late in December, the aromatic groves appeared in full bloom.', 68071, 0), (442113, 'Retaliation is related to nature and instinct, not to law. Law, by definition, cannot obey the same rules as nature.', 532, 0), (442114, 'I realise that in this undertaking I place myself in a certain opposition to views widely held concerning the mathematical infinite and to opinions frequently defended on the nature of numbers.', 59571, 0), (442115, 'I like all those painters who loved and had a strong feeling for nature.', 70842, 0), (442116, 'It is human nature to hate the man whom you have hurt.', 3582, 0), (442117, 'For sin is just this, what man cannot by its very nature do with his whole being; it is possible to silence the conflict in the soul, but it is not possible to uproot it.', 1938, 0), (442118, 'It seems to me like Mother Nature''s mercy and forgiveness have run dry, as we ceaselessly abuse her and take her for granted in order for us to continue our addiction to using fossil fuels. I''ve gotta say, I don''t blame her. Not one bit.', 70843, 0), (442119, 'We have become frighteningly effective at altering nature.', 67053, 0), (442120, 'Nature deals the cards without thought or care, and there is no point in blaming the dealer. All we can do is make the best of the hands we have been dealt.', 67531, 0), (442121, 'If you look at the common denominator of all the comics who have had big success, it''s being true to their nature... that''s what takes a long time to learn.', 1252, 0), (442122, 'In interior decorating, the pig''s actually quite there. It''s used in paint for the texture, but also for the glossiness. In sandpaper, bone glue is actually the glue between the sand and the paper. And then in paintbrushes, hairs are used because, apparently, they''re very suitable for making paintbrushes because of their hard-wearing nature.', 70844, 0), (442123, 'One always talks of surrendering to nature. There is also such a thing as surrendering to the picture.', 70198, 0), (442124, 'I do love nature, but I don''t suppose I''d spent more time in zoos as a child than anyone else!', 69023, 0), (442125, 'No matter how much you''ve done before, you wonder if there will be a light at the end of this particular tunnel. It''s the nature of the beast, and it''s a part of what compels us. Every movie is a new lesson you learn making your way through it.', 70845, 0), (442126, 'Whoever dedicates his life to searching out particular connections of nature will spontaneously be confronted with the question how they harmoniously fit into the whole.', 2422, 0), (442127, 'Middle age is the awkward period when Father Time starts catching up with Mother Nature.', 62727, 0), (442128, 'To insult someone we call him ''bestial. For deliberate cruelty and nature, ''human'' might be the greater insult.', 988, 0), (442129, 'Art is nature speeded up and God slowed down.', 21982, 0), (442130, 'I am a leader by default, only because nature does not allow a vacuum.', 2109, 0), (442131, 'It is better to do one''s own duty, however defective it may be, than to follow the duty of another, however well one may perform it. He who does his duty as his own nature reveals it, never sins.', 15, 0), (442132, 'A vacuum is a hell of a lot better than some of the stuff that nature replaces it with.', 355, 0), (442133, 'It is the nature of the artist to mind excessively what is said about him. Literature is strewn with the wreckage of men who have minded beyond reason the opinions of others.', 113, 0), (442134, 'The wit makes fun of other persons; the satirist makes fun of the world; the humorist makes fun of himself, but in so doing, he identifies himself with people - that is, people everywhere, not for the purpose of taking them apart, but simply revealing their true nature.', 1843, 0), (442135, 'The Artist is he who detects and applies the law from observation of the works of Genius, whether of man or Nature. The Artisan is he who merely applies the rules which others have detected.', 1049, 0), (442136, 'I know no subject more elevating, more amazing, more ready to the poetical enthusiasm, the philosophical reflection, and the moral sentiment than the works of nature. Where can we meet such variety, such beauty, such magnificence?', 63383, 0), (442137, 'A politician never forgets the precarious nature of elective life. We have never established a practice of tenure in public office.', 15498, 0), (442138, 'Every step in the progress of this study has tended to obliterate the technical barriers by which logicians have sought to separate the inquiries relating to the several parts of man''s nature.', 70846, 0), (442139, 'I love to think of nature as an unlimited broadcasting station, through which God speaks to us every hour, if we will only tune in.', 14728, 0), (442140, 'The fulness of the godhead dwelt in every blade of grass.', 70847, 0), (442141, 'My aim in painting has always been the most exact transcription possible of my most intimate impression of nature.', 19741, 0), (442142, 'Where there are large powers with little ambition... nature may be said to have fallen short of her purposes.', 995, 0), (442143, 'Occurrences in this domain are beyond the reach of exact prediction because of the variety of factors in operation, not because of any lack of order in nature.', 104, 0), (442144, 'Happy the man whose wish and care a few paternal acres bound, content to breathe his native air in his own ground.', 3348, 0), (442145, 'Land really is the best art.', 321, 0), (442146, 'When nature has work to be done, she creates a genius to do it.', 760, 0), (442147, 'Nature, to be commanded, must be obeyed.', 1035, 0), (442148, 'Nature is not human hearted.', 15, 0), (442149, 'All things are artificial, for nature is the art of God.', 4506, 0), (442150, 'The old cathedrals are good, but the great blue dome that hangs over everything is better.', 3061, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442151, 'As the twig is bent the tree inclines.', 1462, 0), (442152, 'Go forth under the open sky, and list To Nature''s teachings.', 70801, 0), (442153, 'I am two with nature.', 281, 0), (442154, 'Nature is the master of talents genius is the master of nature. ', 62532, 0), (442155, 'Nature hasn''t gone anywhere. It is all around us, all the planets, galaxies and so on. We are nothing in comparison.', 1556, 0), (442156, 'Vegetation is the basic instrument the creator uses to set all of nature in motion.', 24795, 0), (442157, 'I''ve always regarded nature as the clothing of God.', 70848, 0), (442158, 'All the universe is full of the lives of perfect creatures.', 54701, 0), (442159, 'Bats drink on the wing, like swallows, by sipping the surface, as they play over pools and streams.', 70849, 0), (442160, 'Nature was my kindergarten.', 70850, 0), (442161, 'I have seen the movement of the sinews of the sky, And the blood coursing in the veins of the moon.', 8809, 0), (442162, 'Nature''s far too subtle to repeat herself.', 70851, 0), (442163, 'People in cities may forget the soil for as long as a hundred years, but Mother Nature''s memory is long and she will not let them forget indefinitely.', 70852, 0), (442164, 'He who does not become familiar with nature through love will never know her.', 68443, 0), (442165, 'In nature there are few sharp lines.', 7259, 0), (442166, 'Nature does not proceed in a straight line, it is rather a sprawling development.', 31170, 0), (442167, 'In our nature, however, there is a provision, alike marvelous and merciful, that the sufferer should never know the intensity of what he endures by its present torture, but chiefly by the pang that rankles after it.', 650, 0), (442168, 'The system of nature, of which man is a part, tends to be self-balancing, self-adjusting, self-cleansing. Not so with technology.', 66889, 0), (442169, 'No further evidence is needed to show that ''mental illness'' is not the name of a biological condition whose nature awaits to be elucidated, but is the name of a concept whose purpose is to obscure the obvious.', 1678, 0), (442170, 'Copy nature and you infringe on the work of our Lord. Interpret nature and you are an artist.', 70853, 0), (442171, 'To be perfectly just is an attribute of the divine nature; to be so to the utmost of our abilities, is the glory of man.', 2868, 0), (442172, 'Corruption is nature''s way of restoring our faith in democracy.', 2206, 0), (442173, 'The big artist keeps an eye on nature and steals her tools.', 63435, 0), (442174, 'Man masters nature not by force but by understanding. This is why science has succeeded where magic failed: because it has looked for no spell to cast over nature.', 2921, 0), (442175, 'Nature made the fields and man the cities.', 65718, 0), (442176, 'Speech is human nature itself, with none of the artificiality of written language.', 2606, 0), (442177, 'He who asks of life nothing but the improvement of his own nature... is less liable than anyone else to miss and waste life.', 4754, 0), (442178, 'Tears are nature''s lotion for the eyes. The eyes see better for being washed by them.', 6105, 0), (442179, 'Disease is the retribution of outraged Nature.', 32228, 0), (442180, 'Nature is garrulous to the point of confusion, let the artist be truly taciturn.', 10097, 0), (442181, 'Poetry is emotion put into measure. The emotion must come by nature, but the measure can be acquired by art.', 552, 0), (442182, 'Why is it so painful to watch a person sink? Because there is something unnatural in it, for nature demands personal progress, evolution, and every backward step means wasted energy.', 8978, 0), (442183, 'Resentment seems to have been given us by nature for a defense, and for a defense only! It is the safeguard of justice and the security of innocence.', 2485, 0), (442184, 'It is the nature of every person to error, but only the fool perseveres in error.', 1306, 0), (442185, 'But is it not the fact that religion emanates from the nature, from the moral state of the individual? Is it not therefore true that unless the nature be completely exercised, the moral state harmonized, the religion cannot be healthy?', 34936, 0), (442186, 'One pits his wits against apparently inscrutable nature, wooing her with ardor but nature is blind justice who cannot recognize personal identity.', 70854, 0), (442187, 'By nature and doctrines I am addicted to the habit of discovering choice places wherein to feed.', 15417, 0), (442188, 'All the mathematical sciences are founded on relations between physical laws and laws of numbers, so that the aim of exact science is to reduce the problems of nature to the determination of quantities by operations with numbers.', 70855, 0), (442189, 'The mission of art is to represent nature not to imitate her.', 70856, 0), (442190, 'It is a governing principle of nature, that the agency which can produce most good, when perverted from its proper aim, is most productive of evil.', 66833, 0), (442191, 'Every man has a certain sphere of discretion which he has a right to expect shall not be infringed by his neighbours. This right flows from the very nature of man.', 20151, 0), (442192, 'Perhaps many of the perplexing problems of the new music could be put into a new light if we were to reintroduce the ancient idea of music being a reflection of nature.', 70808, 0), (442193, 'When I conform to truth, I do not conform to an abstract principle; I conform to the nature of God.', 69533, 0), (442194, 'It''s hard to say what drives a three year-old, but I think I had a sense that nature was my solace, and nature was a place in which there was beauty, in which there was order.', 67502, 0), (442195, 'Habituated from our Infancy to trample upon the Rights of Human Nature, every generous, every liberal Sentiment, if not extinguished, is enfeebled in our Minds.', 65391, 0), (442196, 'The most general law in nature is equity-the principle of balance and symmetry which guides the growth of forms along the lines of the greatest structural efficiency.', 18446, 0), (442197, 'How does a pansy, for example, select the ingredients from soil to get the right colors for the flower? Now there''s a great miracle. I think there''s a supreme power behind all of this. I see it in nature.', 69955, 0), (442198, 'What nature requires is obtainable, and within easy reach. It is for the superfluous we sweat.', 65434, 0), (442199, 'Except during the nine months before he draws his first breath, no man manages his affairs as well as a tree does.', 266, 0), (442200, 'Nature has always had more force than education.', 808, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442201, 'The connections I draw between human nature and political systems in my new book, for example, were prefigured in the debates during the Enlightenment and during the framing of the American Constitution.', 3432, 0), (442202, 'We cannot command Nature except by obeying her.', 1035, 0), (442203, 'Nature, like man, sometimes weeps from gladness.', 1827, 0), (442204, 'Spring beckons! All things to the call respond the trees are leaving and cashiers abscond. ', 224, 0), (442205, 'If you look deep enough you will see music the heart of nature being everywhere music. ', 3061, 0), (442206, 'They are much to be pitied who have not been given a taste for nature early in life.', 24, 0), (442207, 'Nature teaches more than she preaches. There are no sermons in stones. It is easier to get a spark out of a stone than a moral.', 1069, 0), (442208, 'All are but parts of one stupendous whole, Whose body Nature is, and God the soul.', 3348, 0), (442209, 'Good nature is worth more than knowledge, more than money, more than honor, to the persons who possess it.', 2175, 0), (442210, 'Let us permit nature to have her way. She understands her business better than we do.', 663, 0), (442211, 'The sky is the part of creation in which nature has done for the sake of pleasing man.', 485, 0), (442212, 'It is a sign of a dull nature to occupy oneself deeply in matters that concern the body; for instance, to be over much occupied about exercise, about eating and drinking, about easing oneself, about sexual intercourse.', 56730, 0), (442213, 'No one likes to have less than they had before. That''s the nature of the human animal.', 16696, 0), (442214, 'The world is always in movement.', 14772, 0), (442215, '''Healing,'' Papa would tell me, ''is not a science, but the intuitive art of wooing nature.''', 219, 0), (442216, 'Man has lost the capacity to foresee and to forestall. He will end by destroying the earth.', 1006, 0), (442217, 