), (442232, 'It is only in the country that we can get to know a person or a book.', 9518, 0), (442233, 'Like water, we are truest to our nature in repose.', 9518, 0), (442234, 'The modern period adds social ethics to religions agenda, for we now realize that social structures are not like laws of nature. They are human creations, so we are responsible for them.', 7993, 0), (442235, 'Read nature nature is a friend to truth. ', 4028, 0), (442236, 'Men must necessarily be the active agents of their own well-being and well-doing they themselves must in the very nature of things be their own best helpers.', 7329, 0), (442237, 'Poor, dear, silly Spring, preparing her annual surprise!', 2547, 0), (442238, 'The scientist does not study nature because it is useful; he studies it because he delights in it, and he delights in it because it is beautiful.', 30572, 0), (442239, 'A scientist worthy of his name, about all a mathematician, experiences in his work the same impression as an artist; his pleasure is as great and of the same nature.', 30572, 0), (442240, 'If we knew exactly the laws of nature and the situation of the universe at the initial moment, we could predict exactly the situation of the same universe at a succeeding moment.', 30572, 0), (442241, 'All nature wears one universal grin.', 9977, 0), (442242, 'It belongs to human nature to hate those you have injured.', 3582, 0), (442243, 'Occasionally I have come across a last patch of snow on top of a mountain in late May or June. There''s something very powerful about finding snow in summer.', 19810, 0), (442244, 'Beauty is nature''s brag, and must be shown in courts, at feasts, and high solemnities, where most may wonder at the workmanship.', 465, 0), (442245, 'Nature is a good name for an effect whose cause is God.', 8676, 0), (442246, 'Umpires are necessary evils. That''s just the nature of the beast. For years, people have looked on umpiring as a job they could get any postman to do.', 70857, 0), (442247, 'To destroy is still the strongest instinct in nature.', 17074, 0), (442248, 'The historic ascent of humanity, taken as a whole, may be summarized as a succession of victories of consciousness over blind forces - in nature, in society, in man himself.', 1626, 0), (442249, 'Death is the ugly fact which Nature has to hide, and she hides it well.', 13963, 0), (442250, 'Understanding the laws of nature does not mean that we are immune to their operations.', 2781, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442251, 'The earth is yet the place of the domicile of man and all the offspring of the first man.', 70858, 0), (442252, 'Poetry is the key to the hieroglyphics of nature.', 9797, 0), (442253, 'Nearness to nature... keeps the spirit sensitive to impressions not commonly felt and in touch with the unseen powers.', 70859, 0), (442254, 'What must be the nature of the world... if human beings are able to introduce changes into it?', 67590, 0), (442255, 'I think there''s a supreme power behind the whole thing, an intelligence. Look at all of the instincts of nature, both animals and plants, the very ingenious ways they survive. If you cut yourself, you don''t have to think about it.', 69955, 0), (442256, 'Human beings are accustomed to think of intellect as the power of having and controlling ideas and of ability to learn as synonymous with ability to have ideas. But learning by having ideas is really one of the rare and isolated events in nature.', 70823, 0), (442257, 'Nothing is farther than earth from heaven nothing is nearer than heaven to earth. ', 67993, 0), (442258, 'The sun, the earth, love, friends, our very breath are parts of the banquet.', 23215, 0), (442259, 'Physics does not change the nature of the world it studies, and no science of behavior can change the essential nature of man, even though both sciences yield technologies with a vast power to manipulate the subject matters.', 3779, 0), (442260, 'I love the long grass coming up to meet the willows.', 70860, 0), (442261, 'Where hast thou wandered, gentle gale, to find the perfumes thou dost bring?', 70801, 0), (442262, 'Families, particularly, tend to be the ones that you take the most for granted. They seem to slip under the radar, all those important things - it almost becomes second nature to do so.', 69259, 0), (442263, 'It is one thing for the human mind to extract from the phenomena of nature the laws which it has itself put into them it may be a far harder thing to extract laws over which it has no control. ', 67599, 0), (442264, 'A tree is an incomprehensible mystery.', 24741, 0), (442265, 'The snow itself is lonely or, if you prefer, self-sufficient. There is no other time when the whole world seems composed of one thing and one thing only.', 38001, 0), (442266, 'We are embedded in a biological world and related to the organisms around us.', 70610, 0), (442267, 'Sensitive, responsive, eagerly welcomed everywhere, the drama, holding the mirror up to nature, by laughter and by tears reveals to mankind the world of men.', 70861, 0), (442268, 'Sound is the vocabulary of nature.', 70862, 0), (442269, 'There are unknown forces in nature; when we give ourselves wholly to her, without reserve, she lends them to us; she shows us these forms, which our watching eyes do not see, which our intelligence does not understand or suspect.', 2591, 0), (442270, 'Nature is inside art as its content, not outside as its model.', 16214, 0), (442271, 'I suppose I might insist on making issues of things. But that is not my nature, and I always bear in mind that my mission is to leave behind me the kind of impression that will make it easier for those who follow.', 15432, 0), (442272, 'We talk of our mastery of nature, which sounds very grand; but the fact is we respectfully adapt ourselves, first, to her ways.', 62206, 0), (442273, 'Those little nimble musicians of the air, that warble forth their curious ditties, with which nature hath furnished them to the shame of art.', 62724, 0), (442274, 'Man is nature''s sole mistake.', 70863, 0), (442275, 'In June as many as a dozen species may burst their buds on a single day. No man can heed all of these anniversaries no man can ignore all of them. ', 1954, 0), (442276, 'A structure becomes architectural, and not sculptural, when its elements no longer have their justification in nature.', 1053, 0), (442277, 'What law, what reason can deny that gift so sweet, so natural that God has given a stream, a fish, a beast, a bird?', 84, 0), (442278, 'There is no forgiveness in nature.', 61075, 0), (442279, 'Man is the miracle in nature. God Is the One Miracle to man.', 65279, 0), (442280, 'It is easy to replace man, and it will take no great time, when Nature has lapsed, to replace Nature.', 62853, 0), (442281, 'For every person who has ever lived there has come, at last, a spring he will never see. Glory then in the springs that are yours.', 15447, 0), (442282, 'Custom, that is before all law; Nature, that is above all art.', 69069, 0), (442283, 'Man''s heart away from nature becomes hard.', 70864, 0), (442284, 'But when, in the first setting out, he takes it for granted without proof, that distinctions found in the structure of all languages, have no foundation in nature; this surely is too fastidious a way of treating the common sense of mankind.', 62998, 0), (442285, 'The sky lovingly smiles on the earth and her children.', 70865, 0), (442286, 'Cruelty is a part of nature, at least of human nature, but it is the one thing that seems unnatural to us.', 4270, 0), (442287, 'When a fantasy turns you on, you''re obligated to God and nature to start doing it - right away.', 54531, 0), (442288, 'Maybe nature is fundamentally ugly, chaotic and complicated. But if it''s like that, then I want out.', 3950, 0), (442289, 'By religion, then, I understand a propitiation or conciliation of powers superior to man which are believed to direct and control the course of nature and of human life.', 70866, 0), (442290, 'The cool wind blew in my face and all at once I felt as if I had shed dullness from myself. Before me lay a long gray line with a black mark down the center. The birds were singing. It was spring.', 70867, 0), (442291, 'The sight of nature fascinates, the family tie has a sweet enchantment and patriotism gives the religious spirit a fiery devotion to the powers that it reveres.', 70868, 0), (442292, 'Nature is my springboard. From her I get my initial impetus. I have tried to relate the visible drama of mountains, trees, and bleached fields with the fantasy of wind blowing and changing colors and forms.', 65055, 0), (442293, 'The nature of anguish is translated into different forms.', 70869, 0), (442294, 'Nature''s laws must be obeyed, and the period of decline begins, and goes on with accelerated rapidity.', 70870, 0), (442295, 'I didn''t want to tell the tree or weed what it was. I wanted it to tell me something and through me express its meaning in nature.', 70871, 0), (442296, 'Nature can refuse to speak but she cannot give a wrong answer.', 70854, 0), (442297, 'The science of today is the technology of tomorrow.', 9104, 0), (442298, 'Only two things are infinite, the universe and human stupidity, and I''m not sure about the former.', 104, 0), (442299, 'Science is a beautiful gift to humanity we should not distort it. ', 1798, 0), (442300, 'Success is a science; if you have the conditions, you get the result.', 40, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442301, 'The art and science of asking questions is the source of all knowledge.', 70872, 0), (442302, 'Democracy is the art and science of running the circus from the monkey cage.', 411, 0), (442303, 'If civilization is to survive, we must cultivate the science of human relationships - the ability of all peoples, of all kinds, to live together, in the same world at peace.', 2261, 0), (442304, 'Science has not yet taught us if madness is or is not the sublimity of the intelligence.', 49, 0), (442305, 'Engineering or technology is all about using the power of science to make life better for people, to reduce cost, to improve comfort, to improve productivity, etc.', 66606, 0), (442306, 'Science is about knowing engineering is about doing. ', 67673, 0), (442307, 'Art is the tree of life. Science is the tree of death.', 221, 0), (442308, 'We live in a society exquisitely dependent on science and technology, in which hardly anyone knows anything about science and technology.', 133, 0), (442309, 'The most beautiful thing we can experience is the mysterious. It is the source of all true art and science.', 104, 0), (442310, 'Science knows no country, because knowledge belongs to humanity, and is the torch which illuminates the world.', 30023, 0), (442311, 'We will always have STEM with us. Some things will drop out of the public eye and will go away, but there will always be science, engineering, and technology. And there will always, always be mathematics.', 70564, 0), (442312, 'Science is fun. Science is curiosity. We all have natural curiosity. Science is a process of investigating. It''s posing questions and coming up with a method. It''s delving in.', 69837, 0), (442313, 'Science is beautiful when it makes simple explanations of phenomena or connections between different observations. Examples include the double helix in biology and the fundamental equations of physics.', 1222, 0), (442314, 'Once you have an innovation culture, even those who are not scientists or engineers - poets, actors, journalists - they, as communities, embrace the meaning of what it is to be scientifically literate. They embrace the concept of an innovation culture. They vote in ways that promote it. They don''t fight science and they don''t fight technology.', 404, 0), (442315, 'Our scientific power has outrun our spiritual power. We have guided missiles and misguided men.', 21767, 0), (442316, 'To raise new questions, new possibilities, to regard old problems from a new angle, requires creative imagination and marks real advance in science.', 104, 0), (442317, 'Science means constantly walking a tightrope between blind faith and curiosity; between expertise and creativity; between bias and openness; between experience and epiphany; between ambition and passion; and between arrogance and conviction - in short, between an old today and a new tomorrow.', 70873, 0), (442318, 'Research is what I''m doing when I don''t know what I''m doing.', 5463, 0), (442319, 'Science and technology revolutionize our lives, but memory, tradition and myth frame our response.', 70874, 0), (442320, 'The most exciting phrase to hear in science, the one that heralds new discoveries, is not ''Eureka!'' but ''That''s funny...''', 988, 0), (442321, 'The whole of science is nothing more than a refinement of everyday thinking.', 104, 0), (442322, 'Everything is theoretically impossible, until it is done.', 17, 0), (442323, 'The science tells us that if we fail to reduce global warming pollution, global temperatures will rise to dangerous levels and unleash devastating extreme weather events and accelerate destructive sea level rise.', 67862, 0), (442324, 'There is no science in this world like physics. Nothing comes close to the precision with which physics enables you to understand the world around you. It''s the laws of physics that allow us to say exactly what time the sun is going to rise. What time the eclipse is going to begin. What time the eclipse is going to end.', 404, 0), (442325, 'Genetic engineering is a result of science advancement, so I don''t think that in itself is bad. If used wisely, genetics can be beneficial, but they can be abused, too.', 68909, 0), (442326, 'The function of sociology, as of every science, is to reveal that which is hidden.', 19821, 0), (442327, 'No amount of experimentation can ever prove me right a single experiment can prove me wrong. ', 104, 0), (442328, 'Science is the key to our future, and if you don''t believe in science, then you''re holding everybody back.', 13455, 0), (442329, 'The rise of Google, the rise of Facebook, the rise of Apple, I think are proof that there is a place for computer science as something that solves problems that people face every day.', 4910, 0), (442330, 'You can be creative in anything - in math, science, engineering, philosophy - as much as you can in music or in painting or in dance.', 10408, 0), (442331, 'Most people say that it is the intellect which makes a great scientist. They are wrong: it is character.', 104, 0), (442332, 'At its heart, engineering is about using science to find creative, practical solutions. It is a noble profession.', 65677, 0), (442333, 'A scientific truth does not triumph by convincing its opponents and making them see the light, but rather because its opponents eventually die and a new generation grows up that is familiar with it.', 2159, 0), (442334, 'Science is what you know, philosophy is what you don''t know.', 95, 0), (442335, 'Ignorance more frequently begets confidence than does knowledge: it is those who know little, and not those who know much, who so positively assert that this or that problem will never be solved by science.', 1024, 0), (442336, 'Science fiction is any idea that occurs in the head and doesn''t exist yet, but soon will, and will change everything for everybody, and nothing will ever be the same again. As soon as you have an idea that changes some small part of the world you are writing science fiction. It is always the art of the possible, never the impossible.', 567, 0), (442337, 'We are born at a given moment, in a given place and, like vintage years of wine, we have the qualities of the year and of the season of which we are born. Astrology does not lay claim to anything more.', 28934, 0), (442338, 'My social philosophy may be said to be enshrined in three words: liberty, equality and fraternity. Let no one, however, say that I have borrowed by philosophy from the French Revolution. I have not. My philosophy has roots in religion and not in political science. I have derived them from the teachings of my Master, the Buddha.', 5224, 0), (442339, 'Travel stories teach geography; insect stories lead the child into natural science; and so on. The teacher, in short, can use reading to introduce her pupils to the most varied subjects; and the moment they have been thus started, they can go on to any limit guided by the single passion for reading.', 11408, 0), (442340, 'Medicine is not only a science; it is also an art. It does not consist of compounding pills and plasters; it deals with the very processes of life, which must be understood before they may be guided.', 2652, 0), (442341, 'To me, mathematics, computer science, and the arts are insanely related. They''re all creative expressions.', 66947, 0), (442342, 'There is nothing which can better deserve your patronage, than the promotion of science and literature. Knowledge is in every country the surest basis of public happiness.', 3161, 0), (442343, 'Science is basically an inoculation against charlatans.', 404, 0), (442344, 'Anthropology demands the open-mindedness with which one must look and listen, record in astonishment and wonder that which one would not have been able to guess.', 992, 0), (442345, 'Our vision is to rediscover the spirit of the Renaissance, create a new discipline where engineering for cultural heritage is actually a symbol of blending art and science together.', 70875, 0), (442346, 'All science is either physics or stamp collecting.', 13421, 0), (442347, 'Every great advance in science has issued from a new audacity of imagination.', 2575, 0), (442348, 'Science is not only a disciple of reason but, also, one of romance and passion.', 1222, 0), (442349, 'Neuroscience is by far the most exciting branch of science because the brain is the most fascinating object in the universe. Every human brain is different - the brain makes each human unique and defines who he or she is.', 70876, 0), (442350, 'The true teachers and educators are not those who have learned pedagogy as the science of dealing with children, but those in whom pedagogy has awakened through understanding the human being.', 14254, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442351, 'There''s nothing I believe in more strongly than getting young people interested in science and engineering, for a better tomorrow, for all humankind.', 13455, 0), (442352, 'The greatest advances of civilization, whether in architecture or painting, in science and literature, in industry or agriculture, have never come from centralized government.', 16707, 0), (442353, 'We live in this world in order always to learn industriously and to enlighten each other by means of discussion and to strive vigorously to promote the progress of science and the fine arts.', 611, 0), (442354, 'Usually, girls weren''t encouraged to go to college and major in math and science. My high school calculus teacher, Ms. Paz Jensen, made math appealing and motivated me to continue studying it in college.', 67400, 0), (442355, 'Science is a way of life. Science is a perspective. Science is the process that takes us from confusion to understanding in a manner that''s precise, predictive and reliable - a transformation, for those lucky enough to experience it, that is empowering and emotional.', 3476, 0), (442356, 'Just as the science and art of agriculture depend upon chemistry and botany, so the art of education depends upon physiology and psychology.', 70823, 0), (442357, 'Mars is the only place in the solar system where it''s possible for life to become multi-planetarian.', 10864, 0), (442358, 'We especially need imagination in science. It is not all mathematics, nor all logic, but it is somewhat beauty and poetry.', 6136, 0), (442359, 'Advertising is fundamentally persuasion and persuasion happens to be not a science, but an art.', 66741, 0), (442360, 'I hated science in high school. Technology? Engineering? Math? Why would I ever need this? Little did I realize that music was also about science, technology, engineering and mathematics, all rolled into one.', 68171, 0), (442361, 'Imagination is the Discovering Faculty, pre-eminently. It is that which penetrates into the unseen worlds around us, the worlds of Science.', 70815, 0), (442362, 'Science never solves a problem without creating ten more.', 266, 0), (442363, 'Science literacy is the artery through which the solutions of tomorrow''s problems flow.', 404, 0), (442364, 'Carl Sagan spoke fluently between biology and geology and astrophysics and physics. If you move fluently across those boundaries, you realize that science is everywhere; science is not something you can step around or sweep under the rug.', 404, 0), (442365, 'I don''t believe in the Great Man theory of science or history. There are no great men, just men standing on the shoulders of other men and what they have done.', 18620, 0), (442366, 'No great advance has been made in science, politics, or religion without controversy.', 10577, 0), (442367, 'What use could the humanities be in a digital age? University students focusing on the humanities may end up, at least in their parents'' nightmares, as dog-walkers for those majoring in computer science. But, for me, the humanities are not only relevant but also give us a toolbox to think seriously about ourselves and the world.', 47722, 0), (442368, 'Scientists have become the bearers of the torch of discovery in our quest for knowledge.', 1222, 0), (442369, 'Biochemistry is the science of life. All our life processes - walking, talking, moving, feeding - are essentially chemical reactions. So biochemistry is actually the chemistry of life, and it''s supremely interesting.', 70877, 0), (442370, 'Statistics is the grammar of science.', 18752, 0), (442371, 'Anthropology is the science which tells us that people are the same the whole world over - except when they are different.', 66183, 0), (442372, 'I like science fiction, I like fantasy, I like time travel, so I had this idea: What if you had a phone that could call into the past?', 54, 0), (442373, 'In the big picture, architecture is the art and science of making sure that our cities and buildings fit with the way we want to live our lives.', 69844, 0), (442374, 'I actually started off majoring in computer science, but I knew right away I wasn''t going to stay with it. It was because I had this one professor who was the loneliest, saddest man I''ve ever known. He was a programmer, and I knew that I didn''t want to do whatever he did.', 60269, 0), (442375, 'People think that computer science is the art of geniuses but the actual reality is the opposite, just many people doing things that build on eachother, like a wall of mini stones.', 67214, 0), (442376, 'Is there anything science should not try to explain? Science is knowledge and knowledge is power - power to do good or evil. Sometimes ignorance is bliss.', 13633, 0), (442377, 'The science of operations, as derived from mathematics more especially, is a science of itself, and has its own abstract truth and value.', 70815, 0), (442378, 'There is no science in creativity. If you don''t give yourself room to fail, you won''t innovate.', 30642, 0), (442379, 'We live in a time when science is validating what humans have known throughout the ages: that compassion is not a luxury; it is a necessity for our well-being, resilience, and survival.', 39477, 0), (442380, 'Science can purify religion from error and superstition. Religion can purify science from idolatry and false absolutes.', 66871, 0), (442381, 'Vaccines and antibiotics have made many infectious diseases a thing of the past we''ve come to expect that public health and modern science can conquer all microbes. But nature is a formidable adversary. ', 67068, 0), (442382, 'Science is a wonderful thing if one does not have to earn one''s living at it.', 104, 0), (442383, 'It is a good morning exercise for a research scientist to discard a pet hypothesis every day before breakfast. It keeps him young.', 2533, 0), (442384, 'I am among those who think that science has great beauty.', 1036, 0), (442385, 'Evolution is the fundamental idea in all of life science - in all of biology.', 13455, 0), (442386, 'The kitchen''s a laboratory, and everything that happens there has to do with science. It''s biology, chemistry, physics. Yes, there''s history. Yes, there''s artistry. Yes, to all of that. But what happened there, what actually happens to the food is all science.', 32294, 0), (442387, 'Science fiction writers foresee the inevitable, and although problems and catastrophes may be inevitable, solutions are not.', 988, 0), (442388, 'There are in fact two things, science and opinion; the former begets knowledge, the later ignorance.', 10825, 0), (442389, 'There is science, logic, reason; there is thought verified by experience. And then there is California.', 1370, 0), (442390, 'You could get an entire computer science education for free right now.', 66947, 0), (442391, 'Science and technology are a propellant for building a thriving country, and the happiness of the people and the future of the country hinge on their development.', 67852, 0), (442392, 'The difference between science and the arts is not that they are different sides of the same coin even, or even different parts of the same continuum, but rather, they are manifestations of the same thing. The arts and sciences are avatars of human creativity.', 69859, 0), (442393, 'In science, we must be interested in things, not in persons.', 1036, 0), (442394, 'Music is not math. It''s science. You keep mixing the stuff up until it blows up on you, or it becomes this incredible potion.', 22720, 0), (442395, 'Science is the father of knowledge, but opinion breeds ignorance.', 10825, 0), (442396, 'Mathematical science shows what is. It is the language of unseen relations between things. But to use and apply that language, we must be able fully to appreciate, to feel, to seize the unseen, the unconscious.', 70815, 0), (442397, 'Science cannot progress without reliable and accurate measurement of what it is you are trying to study. The key is measurement, simple as that.', 70878, 0), (442398, 'Medical science has proven time and again that when the resources are provided, great progress in the treatment, cure, and prevention of disease can occur.', 1856, 0), (442399, 'Nothing is less important than which fork you use. Etiquette is the science of living. It embraces everything. It is ethics. It is honor.', 31062, 0), (442400, 'There is a single light of science, and to brighten it anywhere is to brighten it everywhere.', 988, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442401, 'All science requires mathematics. The knowledge of mathematical things is almost innate in us. This is the easiest of sciences, a fact which is obvious in that no one''s brain rejects it; for laymen and people who are utterly illiterate know how to count and reckon.', 10880, 0), (442402, 'I found that people like rules, and I love to tell people what to do. It''s not rocket science when it comes to weight loss. It''s about eating a little less and moving a little bit more.', 70879, 0), (442403, 'Many who have had an opportunity of knowing any more about mathematics confuse it with arithmetic, and consider it an arid science. In reality, however, it is a science which requires a great amount of imagination.', 50056, 0), (442404, 'Adventure upon all the tickets in the lottery, and you lose for certain; and the greater the number of your tickets the nearer your approach to this certainty.', 2485, 0), (442405, 'Part of what made the Macintosh great was that the people working on it were musicians, poets, and artists, and zoologists, and historians. They also happened to be the best computer scientists in the world. But if it hadn''t been computer science, these people would have been doing amazing things in other fields.', 1064, 0), (442406, 'I think of it as a good opportunity to let, in particular, school kids know that this job and other interesting jobs in science and engineering are open to anyone who works hard in school and gets a good education and studies math and science. And that it''s not just for a select group of people.', 67400, 0), (442407, 'Software Engineering might be science; but that''s not what I do. I''m a hacker, not an engineer.', 70880, 0), (442408, 'It has become almost a cliche to remark that nobody boasts of ignorance of literature, but it is socially acceptable to boast ignorance of science and proudly claim incompetence in mathematics.', 1716, 0), (442409, 'Science is the search for truth, that is the effort to understand the world: it involves the rejection of bias, of dogma, of revelation, but not the rejection of morality.', 2104, 0), (442410, 'I''m not much of a math and science guy. I spent most of my time in school daydreaming and managed to turn it into a living.', 1110, 0), (442411, 'Some say they see poetry in my paintings I see only science. ', 70881, 0), (442412, 'I do not recognize the right of the public to break in the front door of a man''s private life in order to satisfy the gaze of the curious... I do not think it right to dissect living men even for the advancement of science. So far as I am concerned, I prefer a post mortem examination to vivisection without anaesthetics.', 2018, 0), (442413, 'Unlike science, creationism cannot predict anything, and it cannot provide satisfactory answers about the past.', 13455, 0), (442414, 'There are two things I enjoy most about my work. First, I get to work with interesting and enthusiastic people who are also fired up about science. Second, every once in a while I have moments in which I suddenly understand the solution to a problem that I''ve been working on - those are great moments.', 70882, 0), (442415, 'Biology is the science. Evolution is the concept that makes biology unique.', 7867, 0), (442416, 'Science is the captain, and practice the soldiers.', 1386, 0), (442417, 'When we see the shadow on our images, are we seeing the time 11 minutes ago on Mars? Or are we seeing the time on Mars as observed from Earth now? It''s like time travel problems in science fiction. When is now; when was then?', 13455, 0), (442418, 'The method of political science is the interpretation of life; its instrument is insight, a nice understanding of subtle, unformulated conditions.', 1970, 0), (442419, 'Raising children is a creative endeavor, an art rather than a science.', 20155, 0), (442420, 'The conscience of the world is so guilty that it always assumes that people who investigate heresies must be heretics; just as if a doctor who studies leprosy must be a leper. Indeed, it is only recently that science has been allowed to study anything without reproach.', 2200, 0), (442421, 'In science there is only physics all the rest is stamp collecting. ', 65578, 0), (442422, 'It is science, and not religion, which has taught men that things are complex and difficult to understand.', 15804, 0), (442423, 'Science, as illustrated by the printing press, the telegraph, the railway, is a double-edged sword. At the same moment that it puts an enormous power in the hands of the good man, it also offers an equal advantage to the evil disposed.', 69945, 0), (442424, 'Science is magic that works.', 13666, 0), (442425, 'I feel like the thing we can do is celebrate people doing great work and create more cultural momentum and awareness that this is an important thing in the world. So when the next economic crisis hits and people are talking about where to cut from the budget, science isn''t the thing.', 5553, 0), (442426, 'The science of the mind can only have for its proper goal the understanding of human nature by every human being, and through its use, brings peace to every human soul.', 29457, 0), (442427, 'There''s no question that as science, knowledge and technology advance, that we will attempt to do more significant things. And there''s no question that we will always have to temper those things with ethics.', 1793, 0), (442428, 'The thing I have discovered about working with personal finance is that the good news is that it is not rocket science. Personal finance is about 80 percent behavior. It is only about 20 percent head knowledge.', 5846, 0), (442429, 'The whole of science, and one is tempted to think the whole of the life of any thinking man, is trying to come to terms with the relationship between yourself and the natural world. Why are you here, and how do you fit in, and what''s it all about.', 3969, 0), (442430, '''Snow White'' is an old fairy tale, so obviously the idea of vanity and obsession with youth is long-standing. With today''s science, people have become crazy with trying to move their face around. It''s bizarre.', 64247, 0), (442431, 'I felt that chess... is a science in the form of a game... I consider myself a scientist. I wanted to be treated like a scientist.', 38353, 0), (442432, 'The heart of science is measurement.', 70138, 0), (442433, 'There does not exist a category of science to which one can give the name applied science. There are science and the applications of science, bound together as the fruit of the tree which bears it.', 30023, 0), (442434, 'Transhumanism is the ethics and science of using things like biological and genetic engineering to transform our bodies and make us a more powerful species.', 1518, 0), (442435, 'Mild autism can give you a genius like Einstein. If you have severe autism, you could remain nonverbal. You don''t want people to be on the severe end of the spectrum. But if you got rid of all the autism genetics, you wouldn''t have science or art. All you would have is a bunch of social ''yak yaks.''', 11095, 0), (442436, 'Science provides an understanding of a universal experience. Arts provide a universal understanding of a personal experience.', 69859, 0), (442437, 'If an elderly but distinguished scientist says that something is possible, he is almost certainly right; but if he says that it is impossible, he is very probably wrong.', 1004, 0), (442438, 'To begin with, we put the proposition: pure phenomenology is the science of pure consciousness.', 2548, 0), (442439, 'Architecture is a science arising out of many other sciences, and adorned with much and varied learning; by the help of which a judgment is formed of those works which are the result of other arts.', 53497, 0), (442440, 'I hate to tell you this, but you will never actually go to a galaxy far, far away and encounter Darth Vader. That''s science fiction; it isn''t going to happen.', 114, 0), (442441, 'Most great advances have been a collaboration. That is the joy of science for me.', 70883, 0), (442442, 'As long as men are free to ask what they must, free to say what they think, free to think what they will, freedom can never be lost and science can never regress.', 450, 0), (442443, 'But man has still another powerful resource: natural science with its strictly objective methods.', 67927, 0), (442444, 'A permanent base on Mars would have a number of advantages beyond being a bonanza for planetary science and geology. If, as some evidence suggests, exotic micro-organisms have arisen independently of terrestrial life, studying them could revolutionise biology, medicine and biotechnology.', 13633, 0), (442445, 'One of the most interesting things about science fiction and fantasy is the way that the genres can offer different perspectives on matters to do with the body, the mind, medical technology, and the way we live our lives.', 70884, 0), (442446, 'There are no shortcuts in evolution.', 16727, 0), (442447, 'Science is simply common sense at its best, that is, rigidly accurate in observation, and merciless to fallacy in logic.', 63366, 0), (442448, 'We can lick gravity, but sometimes the paperwork is overwhelming.', 5463, 0), (442449, 'Why do we do basic research? To learn about ourselves.', 70610, 0), (442450, 'Sadly, embryonic stem cell research is completely legal in this country and has been going on at universities and research facilities for years.', 66593, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (442451, 'Scientific research is one of the most exciting and rewarding of occupations.', 60557, 0), (442452, 'Perfect as the wing of a bird may be, it will never enable the bird to fly if unsupported by the air. Facts are the air of science. Without them a man of science can never rise.', 67927, 0), (442453, 'Cooking is for chefs. Science informs us and lets us cook while knowing what we are doing, but it is not a replacement for the skills of a chef.', 10715, 0), (442454, 'A fool''s brain digests philosophy into folly, science into superstition, and art into pedantry. Hence University education.', 266, 0), (442455, 'Science is the best idea humans have ever had. The more people who embrace that idea, the better.', 13455, 0), (442456, 'The main purpose of science is simplicity and as we understand more things, everything is becoming simpler.', 9104, 0), (442457, 'We''re as clever as we think we are, but we''ll be a lot cleverer when we learn to use not just one brain but to pool huge numbers of brains. We''re at a level technologically where we can share information and think collectively about our problems. We do it in science all the time - there''s no reason why we can''t do it in other endeavors.', 3484, 0), (442458, 'I''ve always felt that the human-centered approach to computer science leads to more interesting, more exotic, more wild, and more heroic adventures than the machine-supremacy approach, where information is the highest goal.', 2743, 0), (442459, 'False facts are highly injurious to the progress of science, for they often endure long; but false views, if supported by some evidence, do little harm, for every one takes a salutary pleasure in proving their falseness.', 1024, 0), (442460, 'No science is immune to the infection of politics and the corruption of power.', 2921, 0), (442461, 'Skeptical scrutiny is the means, in both science and religion, by which deep thoughts can be winnowed from deep nonsense.', 133, 0), (442462, 'The product of mental labor - science - always stands far below its value, because the labor-time necessary to reproduce it has no relation at all to the labor-time required for its original production.', 1336, 0), (442463, 'Science may be described as the art of systematic over-simplification.', 20892, 0), (442464, 'The proper study of mankind is the science of design.', 2920, 0), (442465, 'I am aware of the usefulness of science to society and of the benefits society derives from it.', 69853, 0), (442466, 'It is not enough to know your craft - you have to have feeling. Science is all very well, but for us imagination is worth far more.', 19835, 0), (442467, 'If there were a science of human beings it would be anthropology that aims at understanding the totality of experience through structural context.', 70885, 0), (442468, 'Science must begin with myths, and with the criticism of myths.', 20892, 0), (442469, 'The man of science is a poor philosopher.', 104, 0), (442470, 'Human Nature is the only science of man and yet has been hitherto the most neglected. ', 2498, 0), (442471, 'If science fiction is the mythology of modern technology, then its myth is tragic.', 77, 0), (442472, 'The science linking the increased frequency and severity of extreme weather to the climate crisis has matured tremendously in the last couple of years.', 13473, 0), (442473, 'What has become clear from the science is that we cannot burn all of the fossil fuels without creating a very different planet.', 70886, 0), (442474, 'Men have been obliged to make for themselves a notion of what religion is, long before the science of religions started its methodical comparisons.', 15804, 0), (442475, 'Comparing science and religion isn''t like comparing apples and oranges - it''s more like apples and sewing machines.', 48964, 0), (442476, 'I just had a crazy, wild imagination all my life, and science fiction is the greatest outlet for me.', 5194, 0), (442477, 'The thrill of science is the process. It''s a social process. It''s a process of collective discovery. It''s debate, it''s experimentation and it''s verification of claims that might be false. It''s the greatest foundation for a society.', 10504, 0), (442478, 'I think the least important thing about science fiction for me is its predictive capacity.', 9661, 0), (442479, 'It is no coincidence that so many religious beliefs date back to times when no science could possibly have accounted satisfactorily for many of the natural phenomena inspiring scripture and myths.', 13403, 0), (442480, 'Science is a first-rate piece of furniture for a man''s upper chamber, if he has common sense on the ground-floor. But if a man hasn''t got plenty of good common sense, the more science he has, the worse for his patient.', 24754, 0), (442481, 'You should never bet against anything in science at odds of more than about 1012 to 1.', 13421, 0), (442482, 'Religion is something left over from the infancy of our intelligence, it will fade away as we adopt reason and science as our guidelines.', 95, 0), (442483, 'Political ideology can corrupt the mind, and science.', 44747, 0), (442484, 'In contemporary art culture, where good looks and clever strategic planning of art careers have become a feature, professional practice may be taught in art schools like a branch of public relations or political science.', 10407, 0), (442485, 'As a child I always steered clear of science fiction, but in the autumn of 1977, the bow-wave of publicity for the first ''Star Wars'' movie had already reached me, so I was eager for anything science-fictional.', 2721, 0), (442486, 'I read a book called ''The Tao of Physics'' by Fritjof Capra that pointed out the parallels between quantum physics and eastern mysticism. I started to feel there was more to reality than conventional science allowed for and some interesting ideas that it hadn''t got round to investigating, such as altered states of consciousness.', 70887, 0), (442487, 'Science does not know its debt to imagination.', 760, 0), (442488, 'Crucial to science education is hands-on involvement: showing, not just telling; real experiments and field trips and not just ''virtual reality.''', 67022, 0), (442489, 'Science is the international language, so when we are able to convince countries that good decision-making for human health and animal health is based upon science, that''s a real success story for us.', 70888, 0), (442490, 'Sporting competitions seem to be what we obsess over, frankly. So if we can put engineering, science, technology into a format of healthy, fun competition, we can attract all sorts of kids that might not see the kind of activity we do as accessible or rewarding.', 68867, 0), (442491, 'Music is science. Everything is science. Because science is truth.', 67724, 0), (442492, 'Indeed, I would feel that an appreciation of the arts in a conscious, disciplined way might help one to do science better.', 69853, 0), (442493, 'Every science begins as philosophy and ends as art.', 1167, 0), (442494, 'On the ordinary view of each species having been independently created, we gain no scientific explanation.', 1024, 0), (442495, 'Nobody climbs mountains for scientific reasons. Science is used to raise money for the expeditions, but you really climb for the hell of it.', 12199, 0), (442496, 'Geologists have a saying - rocks remember.', 2004, 0), (442497, 'Science is like a love affair with nature; an elusive, tantalising mistress. It has all the turbulence, twists and turns of romantic love, but that''s part of the game.', 68660, 0), (442498, 'Everything, however complicated - breaking waves, migrating birds, and tropical forests - is made of atoms and obeys the equations of quantum physics. But even if those equations could be solved, they wouldn''t offer the enlightenment that scientists seek. Each science has its own autonomous concepts and laws.', 67022, 0), (442499, 'My preparation is about precision. It is 